english:
  title: Stele Inscription for Gwangtong Pojae Seonsa Temple
  author: Lee Saekhk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourth year of the present reign, in the winter month of tenth day of the Year of the Fire Snake, the officials gathered—from Door Below the Throne, Lord Yun Hwan of Chilwon; from Advisor to the Crown, Lord Gyeong Bukhung of Cheongwon; from Guardian Advisor, Lord Lee Inim of Gwangpyeong; and many others of highest rank and station—they raised their voices together in memorial, saying:

    "We humbly reflect that our sovereign lord flourishes in the vigor of spring and autumn, that his reverence and filial piety grow daily, that he honors the ancestral shrines and governs the realm. Like frost and dew that move the heart to sorrow, like seasons that remind us of those departed, these sentiments dwell in him day and night. His solemnity and fear of heaven are without measure. Such virtue requires no embellishment.

    "We, your humble servants, bear our duties with trepidation, fearful only that we fail to sustain the great trust placed upon us by the late king, and thus disappoint you, my lord.

    "In the Year of Heavenly Ascendant Xinsi, our late king was but twelve years old when he journeyed to the capital of the Middle Kingdom, where the imperial favor bestowed upon him knew no equal. In the Year of the Ox, he took as his wife the daughter of the Prince of the Guard, traveling thousands of li to the northern court. In the Year of the Hare, returning by imperial command to govern our realm, he received the title Crown Prince. In the second month of the Year of the Snake, on the sixteenth day, the princess departed this life. The officials bestowed upon her the title of the Virtuous, Reverent, Compassionate, and Wise Queen Mother of the Lu Kingdom. In the fourth month, she was interred at the Right Mausoleum. When word reached the capital, the emperor issued a decree elevating her to the rank of the Illustrious and Benevolent Great Princess of the Lu Kingdom—an honor granted because of the emperor's sorrow.

    "In the ninth month of the Year of the Tiger, on the twenty-third day, our late king passed from life. The officials proclaimed him the Great King of Reverence and Filial Piety. In the tenth month, on the day of Geng-Shen, he was laid to rest at the Dark Mausoleum within Gwangtong Pojae Seonsa Temple, that sacred place where the departed spirits of both sovereigns receive perpetual blessing and care.

    "The stone commemorating his deeds was sought by our late king from the lands of the Middle Kingdom, yet before it could be carved, the great works of construction pressed upon us. Now Lord Park Won-gyeong of the Eastern Peak and Lord Park Seong-liang of Mil-yang report that all labor is complete. They humbly request that the record be engraved upon stone.

    "We, your servants, propose that the Minister of Rites, Lee Saek, compose the inscription; that it be written in the elegant hand of the calligrapher; and that it be carved by the seal-cutter. We respectfully petition that this be commanded."

    And the sovereign decreed: "You, Lee Saek, have long served us through your mastery of letters and words, bringing to light the great virtues of our father the former king, spreading his renown for generations untold. Such is your calling. Fulfill it with utmost care."

    I, Lee Saek, tremble at my unworthiness to match such luminous command. Yet I dare not refuse. Let me therefore set down what is true:

    This temple was formerly under the jurisdiction of the Siheung School, though its name was changed many times—once called the Light-Stone Temple, once the Cloud-Stone Temple—as recorded in the Annals of Mountains and Waters. Its peak is named the Celestial Dance, its stream the Divine Wine Pool, each bearing a meaning yet to be revealed. Our late king, profound in the study of the Buddhist teachings and devoted to the Chan school, declared: "The dharma has no duality; how much less so the temples?" He therefore unified the heavenly harmony of the great Dharma schools, bringing all contention to peace. The temple rose among the Ten Great Monasteries, first in rank. He named the valley Light-Stone Valley and gave to the temple the title Gwangtong Pojae Seonsa—"Illuminating All Directions, Delivering All Beings"—that the grace of the Buddha might flow without obstacle and salvation reach without exception.

    When first the princess departed, astronomers and their attendants were sent to survey the sacred ground. They came to Light-Stone Valley and found it auspicious. But the late king, gazing upon the chosen site, instructed the Master of Heavens: "Shift it slightly to the east; avoid the very center. There, when my time comes, I shall rest beside her, neither husband tilted from the true way of unity." Not long after, the king, contemplating the frailty of the aged and the certainty of death, ordered his own mausoleum prepared. When the work began, no minister dared raise a whisper of protest.

    Each spring and autumn, on chosen days, he would ascend to the Light Mausoleum, bow before the spirit tablets, perform the rites, then proceed to the Right Mausoleum, lingering in contemplation as the day waned. When officials received new appointments, they came to give thanks at the temple gate. All who journeyed abroad or returned to court made offering there. The ceremonies grew ever more solemn with the turning years.

    Ah, how ritual arises from feeling, how emotion finds its form in ceremony!

    In the Year of the Lamb, fleeing disorder, the king journeyed southward. By the Year of the Hare, he returned to the capital, establishing his court at the Heungwang Temple south of the city. When thieves crept into the inner chambers at midnight, the king, perceiving their presence, withdrew to a hidden chamber. The Great Princess of the Lu Kingdom sat at its threshold. The brigands drew their blades before her—a moment fraught with peril! Yet they dared not strike. The generals and ministers entered and drove them out. These became the Guardians of the Realm, their protection as steadfast as armor upon the body.

    The Great Princess possessed a nature serene and unmoved, modest and pure—fit to be called the companion of the ancient sage-king. For fifteen years, not a whisper of private request passed her lips. Her service shone like burnished gold. She should have dwelt in glory, crowned with the rewards of virtue. Yet in the tenth month after birth, her strength departed. The grief of the realm cut to the marrow; ten thousand years hence, it shall not be forgotten. Was not this very temple erected as monument to that sorrow?

    Moreover, how can the officials remain idle when the spirit of our departed lord—whose voice no living ear may hear, whose radiance no living eye may behold—rests in that place? Should we not spare no effort to honor him where his earthly form lies entombed? This is why the great ministers were determined that the stone be carved at Light-Stone Temple.

    As for the temple's lands, both ancient and new; its servants and dependents; its treasuries and storehouses; all that sustains its functions—these were bound by iron decree, sealed with golden stamps, sworn upon by king and ministers alike, recorded in the histories, and hidden within the sacred mountains. The oath declares: "The gods of temple and state, the heavens and their dragon guardians, the eight divine protectors—all bear witness from on high. Should anyone break this covenant, may they be utterly destroyed without mercy."

    Need we wait for the stone to be carved before such vows hold power?

    How farsighted were their deliberations!

    The construction began in the spring of the Year of the Rat and was completed in the winter of the Year of the Snake. The Hall of Maitreya, the Hall of Avalokiteshvara, the Library of the Dharma Treasury, the Chamber of Celestial Alignments, the meditation halls within and without—all stand in perfect order. The monks have their quarters, the refectory and guest hall are prepared, storehouses and kitchens attend to all needs, towers for bells and drums rise toward heaven. More than one hundred structures stand in harmony. The beams hook and interlock; the eaves sweep upward like wings in flight, like pheasants ascending to the clouds. The glazed tiles shimmer like scales of jade; the painted timbers glow like sunset clouds. Every instrument for chanting the dharma is complete, every lamp prepared. Not a single necessity is lacking. All stands in perfect sequence, radiant and gleaming.

    Three great assemblies were held to consecrate the work. The mountain temple is now complete. The hearts of all the realm's officials and people find comfort and peace.

    I, Lee Saek, humbly consider the Great King of Reverence and Filial Piety: He possessed clarity of mind and divine wisdom. He embodied sincerity and followed the Way of harmony. In his reverence for heaven and earth, he made sincere offerings to the altars of heaven and earth. In his reverence for ancestors, he performed with his own hands the autumn and winter rites. He first tilled the sacred fields that farmers might follow his example. He repaired the mausoleums of his predecessors, fulfilling the ancient obligation to honor those gone before. He renovated the portrait halls of the sovereigns, leaving them radiant and complete. He honored the civilizations of the center and kept the protocols of princes. This is the highest courtesy under heaven. He served his noble father with perfect filial devotion—this is supreme filial piety under heaven. He established the worthy heir and secured the foundation of the realm—this is the great design under heaven. In resisting encroachment and repelling insult, heaven recognized his wisdom. In deliberating cases and mitigating punishments, heaven honored his clemency. In relieving the poor and succoring the afflicted, heaven praised his benevolence. In releasing life and forbidding killing, heaven witnessed his compassion. Furthermore, he reformed the ancient music, distinguished the proper robes, established court protocols, and revived the ceremonies of ages past. The brilliance of his court far exceeded that of antiquity.

    Yet fate brought hardship, and his years were not prolonged. The people could not receive the full measure of his nurturing care. Alas! Alas! What sorrow this brings!

    All who dwell in this temple and dedicate themselves to its sacred work should say: "I shall bring blessing upon the realm; I shall benefit both the seen and unseen worlds." Would that their words bear fruit!

    I, Lee Saek, bow deeply and reverently offer this inscription:

    *Bright, bright, luminous, radiant—*
    *Such was the virtue of the King of Reverence and Filial Piety.*
    *Solemn, solemn, gracious, gentle—*
    *Such was the bearing of the Great Princess of Lu.*
    *Their love, like strings in harmony,*
    *Became one tomb where now they rest.*
    *On yellow silk the spirits dwell in splendor,*
    *Guarding against all inauspicious shadow.*
    *The temple, now complete and standing,*
    *Shines with gold and jade in glory.*
    *Dragons and elephants tread the sacred ground;*
    *The bells and drums ring out at dawn and dusk.*
    *The offerings are lavish and full;*
    *The wind blows cool and pure.*
    *The spirits descend and ascend the courtyard stairs;*
    *Fragrance rises and moves all hearts.*
    *Blessings flow upon the realm of kings;*
    *Ten thousand generations shall issue forth.*
    *The people find their dwelling-place;*
    *Peace and joy shine upon their faces.*
    *That such perfection has come to be*
    *Springs from the power of the Buddha.*
    *In the vast three realms stretching boundless,*
    *To whom but the Buddha can we turn?*
    *Though rivers may cease to flow,*
    *Though mountains crumble into dust,*
    *This sacred hall of awakening*
    *Shall endure with the realm eternal.*
    *Hear this, ye generations yet to come:*
    *Behold the words carved here in stone.*
